@startuml
skinparam MinClassWidth 140
skinparam linetype ortho
title Comparison: Simple Role (String) vs PartyRoleType Pattern

' ===== OLD APPROACH =====
package "OLD APPROACH - Role as String" #FFE5E5 {
  object Party_Old {
    id: PartyId
  }

  object PartyRole_Old {
    partyId: PartyId
    role: String
  }

  object PartyRelationship_Old {
    id: PartyRelationshipId
    name: String
    validity: Validity
  }

  Party_Old -- PartyRole_Old
  PartyRelationship_Old -up-> PartyRole_Old : from
  PartyRelationship_Old -up-> PartyRole_Old : to

  note right of PartyRole_Old
    <b>SIMPLE but LIMITED</b>

    Pros:
    ✓ Simple to implement
    ✓ Minimal code
    ✓ Easy to understand

    Cons:
    ✗ No metadata (description)
    ✗ No constraints (anyone can play any role)
    ✗ No responsibilities
    ✗ String magic - typos possible
    ✗ Hard to list all role types
    ✗ Validation logic in policies
  end note

  note bottom of PartyRelationship_Old
    Example problems:
    - Can Person be EMPLOYER? (requires policy)
    - Can Organization be EMPLOYEE? (requires policy)
    - What does "CUSTOMER" mean? (no description)
    - What roles exist? (grep code)
  end note
}

' ===== NEW APPROACH =====
package "NEW APPROACH - PartyRoleType Pattern" #E5FFE5 {
  object Party_New {
    id: PartyId
  }

  object PartyRoleType {
    id: PartyRoleTypeId
    name: String
    description: String
  }

  object PartyRoleConstraint {
    isSatisfiedBy(Party): boolean
  }

  object PartyRole_New {
    partyId: PartyId
  }

  object PartyRelationshipType {
    id: PartyRelationshipTypeId
    name: String
    description: String
  }

  object PartyRelationshipConstraint {
    clientRoleName: String
    supplierRoleName: String
  }

  object PartyRelationship_New {
    id: PartyRelationshipId
    validity: Validity
  }

  Party_New -- PartyRole_New
  PartyRole_New -- PartyRoleType : instance of
  PartyRoleType *-- PartyRoleConstraint

  PartyRelationship_New -- PartyRelationshipType : instance of
  PartyRelationshipType *-- PartyRelationshipConstraint

  PartyRelationship_New -up-> PartyRole_New : from
  PartyRelationship_New -up-> PartyRole_New : to

  note right of PartyRoleType
    <b>RICH but MORE COMPLEX</b>

    Pros:
    ✓ Rich metadata
    ✓ Declarative constraints
    ✓ Type catalog (list all types)
    ✓ Extensible (Responsibilities, Capabilities)
    ✓ API manageable
    ✓ Self-documenting
    ✓ Type safety

    Cons:
    ✗ More code
    ✗ More entities
    ✗ Steeper learning curve
  end note

  note bottom of PartyRelationshipType
    Example benefits:
    - EMPLOYEE type: "only Person" constraint
    - EMPLOYER type: "only Organization" constraint
    - CUSTOMER type: full description
    - List all types via API
    - Validation in type, not policy
  end note
}

note bottom
  <b>MIGRATION STRATEGY</b>

  1. Start with simple String-based roles
     Good for MVP, simple domains

  2. Migrate to PartyRoleType when:
     - Need to manage role catalog
     - Need complex constraints
     - Need responsibilities/capabilities
     - Multiple teams/modules use roles

  3. Both can coexist:
     - Core uses PartyRoleType
     - Simple modules use String
     - Facade translates between

  Similar to Product pattern:
  ProductType (catalog) + ProductInstance
  PartyRoleType (catalog) + PartyRole
end note

@enduml
